VALUES
(19, 119, 65, 65, 'kjv', 'Thou hast dealt well with thy servant, O Lord, according unto thy word.', 0, 71, 'theology', 'God''s Faithfulness', 'This verse illustrates the theological concept of God''s faithfulness. Many scholars believe that the assurance of God''s dealings is rooted in His covenant promises. The phrase ''according unto thy word'' emphasizes that God''s actions are consistent with His revealed truth, inviting believers to trust in His reliability and the truth of Scripture as the foundation of their faith.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the faithfulness of God in keeping His promises."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 65, 65, 'kjv', 'Thou hast dealt well with thy servant, O Lord, according unto thy word.', 0, 71, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Dealings', 'What specific ways have you experienced God''s goodness in your life that align with His promises? Reflecting on personal instances allows for a deeper understanding of how God''s faithfulness manifests in daily circumstances, encouraging gratitude and trust in His ongoing work.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 66, 66, 'kjv', 'Teach me good judgment and knowledge: for I have believed thy commandments.', 0, 75, 'connection', 'Seeking Wisdom in Scripture', 'This verse connects well with Proverbs 2:6, which states, ''For the Lord gives wisdom; from his mouth come knowledge and understanding.'' Both passages emphasize the necessity of divine instruction in acquiring wisdom and understanding, highlighting the relationship between faith in God''s commandments and the pursuit of knowledge.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 2:6", "description": "Proverbs emphasizes the source of wisdom and knowledge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 66, 66, 'kjv', 'good judgment', 9, 22, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Good Judgment''', 'טוֹב (tov, H2896) - good, pleasant, agreeable. In the Hebrew context, ''good judgment'' signifies not just intellectual discernment but a moral compass aligned with God''s statutes, reflecting His character and intentions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2896", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''good''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 66, 66, 'kjv', 'for I have believed thy commandments.', 38, 75, 'theology', 'Faith in Commandments', 'This phrase underscores the theological concept of faith as foundational to obedience. Many scholars believe that genuine belief in God’s commandments leads not only to compliance but to an active desire for understanding and wisdom, further reinforcing the believer''s relationship with God.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the link between faith and obedience."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 66, 66, 'kjv', 'Teach me good judgment and knowledge:', 0, 37, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Teaching', 'What role does seeking divine teaching play in your daily decision-making? How might understanding ''good judgment'' as rooted in God''s commandments change your perspective on difficult choices?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 67, 67, 'kjv', 'Before I was afflicted I went astray', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Affliction and Guidance', 'This phrase connects with Hebrews 12:6, which states, ''For whom the Lord loves He chastens.'' The idea of affliction leading to a correction or a return to the right path is a common biblical theme that highlights God''s loving discipline. It suggests that difficulties can serve as a catalyst for spiritual growth and alignment with God''s will.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 12:6", "description": "Illustrates the theme of divine discipline as a form of love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 67, 67, 'kjv', 'but now have I kept thy word.', 38, 67, 'theology', 'Transformation through Obedience', 'Many scholars believe this verse encapsulates the transformative power of God''s word, illustrating the shift from rebellion to obedience. It suggests that true understanding of God''s commands often follows personal trials, emphasizing that adherence to Scripture can lead to spiritual renewal. This aligns with the doctrine of sanctification, where believers grow in holiness through the influence of God''s word.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 67, 67, 'kjv', 'Before I was afflicted I went astray', 0, 36, 'question', 'Reflecting on Affliction', 'In what ways has affliction in your life led to a deeper understanding or commitment to God''s word? How might your experiences of struggle serve to redirect your path towards faithfulness?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 67, 67, 'kjv', 'Before I was afflicted I went astray', 0, 36, 'greek', 'Affliction in Hebrew', 'עָנָה (anah, H6031) - to be afflicted, humbled, or oppressed. This term emphasizes the dual aspect of affliction, both as a state of suffering and as a tool for humility and repentance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6031", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used for affliction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 68, 68, 'kjv', 'Thou art good, and doest good;', 0, 30, 'connection', 'God''s Nature Revealed', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 34:8, ''O taste and see that the Lord is good: blessed is the man that trusteth in him.'' Both verses emphasize the intrinsic goodness of God and invite believers to experience His goodness personally. Understanding God''s nature as fundamentally good encourages trust and reliance on His character.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 34:8", "description": "Highlights the experiential nature of God''s goodness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 68, 68, 'kjv', 'teach me thy statutes.', 31, 53, 'theology', 'Instruction in Righteousness', 'The request for God to teach His statutes reflects a central theme in biblical theology: the importance of divine instruction for living a righteous life. Many scholars believe this underscores the believer''s dependence on God for moral guidance and spiritual growth, aligning with 2 Timothy 3:16-17, which discusses the Scripture''s role in equipping believers for good works.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Timothy 3:16-17", "description": "Affirms the role of Scripture in teaching and equipping believers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 68, 68, 'kjv', 'Thou art good, and doest good;', 0, 30, 'greek', 'Goodness Defined', 'The Hebrew word for ''good'' here is ''טוֹב'' (tov, H2896) - good, pleasant, agreeable. This term emphasizes not only moral goodness but also the aesthetic quality of God’s character, inviting believers to reflect on the beauty of His goodness in creation and in their lives.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2896", "description": "Defines the Hebrew term for goodness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 68, 68, 'kjv', 'teach me thy statutes.', 31, 53, 'question', 'Desire for Understanding', 'What does it mean to actively seek God''s teaching in your life? In what specific areas do you feel a need for divine guidance, and how can you align your actions with His statutes?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 69, 69, 'kjv', 'The proud have forged a lie against me:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Pride and Falsehood', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 12:19, which states, ''Truthful lips endure forever, but a lying tongue is but for a moment.'' The connection emphasizes the contrast between the prideful actions of others and the enduring nature of God''s truth. The Psalmist''s experience of affliction due to lies bears witness to the challenges faced by those who adhere to God''s precepts in the face of opposition.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 12:19", "description": "Highlights the contrast between truth and falsehood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 69, 69, 'kjv', 'but I will keep thy precepts with my whole heart.', 40, 89, 'theology', 'Wholehearted Obedience', 'This declaration reflects a fundamental aspect of biblical obedience: total commitment to God''s commandments. Many scholars believe this emphasizes the covenant relationship between God and His people, where love and adherence to His statutes are paramount. This verse aligns with Matthew 22:37, where Jesus cites the greatest commandment to love God with all one''s heart.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 22:37", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the importance of loving God wholly."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 69, 69, 'kjv', 'The proud have forged a lie against me:', 0, 39, 'question', 'Facing False Accusations', 'How do we respond when faced with false accusations or slander? This verse invites reflection on the importance of maintaining integrity and faithfulness to God''s precepts, despite the challenges posed by prideful individuals. In what ways can we cultivate a heart that delights in God''s law amidst adversity?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 69, 69, 'kjv', 'but I will keep thy precepts with my whole heart.', 40, 89, 'greek', 'Heart and Commitment', 'לֵב (lev, H3820) - heart. In Hebrew, ''lev'' signifies not just the organ but the center of one''s being, including emotions, intentions, and will. This underscores the depth of commitment the Psalmist expresses in keeping God''s precepts, indicating that true obedience flows from a heart fully devoted to God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3820", "description": "Strong''s number for the word ''heart'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 70, 70, 'kjv', 'Their heart is as fat as grease', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Heart Metaphor in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes sentiments found in Psalm 73:7, where the wicked''s hearts are described as ''fat'' due to their prosperity and lack of concern for righteousness. It highlights a biblical theme contrasting the hardened hearts of the proud against the humble adherence to God''s law. Understanding this connection emphasizes the spiritual blindness that can accompany material abundance, reinforcing the psalmist''s choice to delight in God''s statutes instead.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 73:7", "description": "Similar metaphor about the condition of the heart"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 70, 70, 'kjv', 'but I delight in thy law', 33, 57, 'theology', 'Delight in God''s Law', 'This passage suggests that true delight comes from aligning oneself with God''s will and commandments. Many scholars believe that such delight reflects a deep relationship with God, where His teachings are not burdensome but rather a source of joy and fulfillment. This aligns with New Testament teachings, such as in Matthew 11:30, where Jesus describes His yoke as easy, reinforcing the theme of finding joy in obedience.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 11:30", "description": "Jesus speaks of the ease of His yoke"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 70, 70, 'kjv', 'but I delight in thy law', 33, 57, 'question', 'Personal Application of Delight', 'What does it mean to truly delight in God''s law in your daily life? Reflect on how your attitude towards His commandments influences your actions and decisions. Are there areas where you find His teachings burdensome instead of delightful? How can you cultivate a deeper joy in following His ways?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 71, 71, 'kjv', 'It is good for me that I have been afflicted;', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Affliction in Scripture', 'This phrase resonates with James 1:2-3, which encourages believers to consider it pure joy when they face trials, as testing produces perseverance. Both passages suggest that affliction can lead to spiritual growth and deeper understanding of God''s ways. Likewise, Romans 5:3-4 states that suffering produces endurance, character, and hope, indicating a transformative aspect of hardships in the life of a believer.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:2-3", "description": "Encouragement to find joy in trials."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 5:3-4", "description": "Suffering as a source of growth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 71, 71, 'kjv', 'that I might learn thy statutes.', 46, 78, 'theology', 'Purpose of Affliction', 'This passage suggests that affliction serves a divine purpose in the believer''s life, leading to a deeper understanding of God''s statutes. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological principle that God uses trials to teach and refine His people, a concept echoed throughout Scripture. It highlights the importance of viewing hardships not merely as suffering but as opportunities for spiritual education and growth.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the beneficial aspect of affliction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 71, 71, 'kjv', 'It is good for me that I have been afflicted;', 0, 45, 'question', 'Understanding Affliction', 'How can affliction be perceived as good in the context of spiritual growth? What specific lessons have you learned through your own experiences of hardship that align with the teaching of God''s statutes?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 71, 71, 'kjv', 'It is good for me that I have been afflicted;', 0, 45, 'greek', 'Affliction in Hebrew', 'עָנָה (anah, H6031) - to be afflicted, humbled, or oppressed. This term encapsulates the idea that affliction is not merely about suffering but also about being brought low, which can lead to spiritual awakening and a deeper relationship with God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6031", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 72, 72, 'kjv', 'The law of thy mouth is better unto me than thousands of gold and silver.', 0, 73, 'connection', 'Value of God''s Word', 'This verse resonates with Proverbs 3:13-15, which states, ''Happy is the man that findeth wisdom, and the man that getteth understanding. For the merchandise of it is better than the merchandise of silver, and the gain thereof than fine gold.'' Both passages emphasize that spiritual wisdom and understanding derived from God''s word surpass material wealth. This connection highlights the theme of valuing divine truth over earthly riches.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:13-15", "description": "Comparison of wisdom and material wealth"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 72, 72, 'kjv', 'The law of thy mouth is better unto me than thousands of gold and silver.', 0, 73, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Law''', 'תּוֹרָה (torah, H8451) - law, instruction, teaching. This Hebrew term encompasses not just legal statutes but also guidance and teaching from God. The psalmist''s declaration reflects a deep appreciation for the wisdom and instruction found in God''s word, which provides direction for living a fulfilling life, surpassing any material gain.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8451", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''torah''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 72, 72, 'kjv', 'The law of thy mouth is better unto me than thousands of gold and silver.', 0, 73, 'theology', 'Prioritizing God''s Word', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a foundational Christian principle: the supremacy of God''s word in guiding believers'' lives. It suggests that true wealth is not found in material possessions but in the spiritual richness that comes from understanding and adhering to divine teachings. This aligns with the overall message of the Psalms that emphasizes reliance on God''s wisdom.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on valuing God''s law"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 72, 72, 'kjv', 'The law of thy mouth is better unto me than thousands of gold and silver.', 0, 73, 'question', 'Reflection on Value', 'In what ways can we prioritize God''s word over material pursuits in our daily lives? How does recognizing the value of divine instruction impact our decisions and attitudes towards wealth?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 73, 73, 'kjv', 'Thy hands have made me and fashioned me:', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Creation Reference', 'This phrase echoes Genesis 1:27, where God creates humanity in His own image. The connection highlights the intimate relationship between the Creator and His creation, emphasizing that our existence and identity are rooted in God''s intentional design. Understanding this can deepen our appreciation for our worth and purpose as beings fashioned by God''s hands.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:27", "description": "God creates humans in His image, underscoring the theme of divine craftsmanship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 73, 73, 'kjv', 'give me understanding,', 41, 63, 'theology', 'The Role of Divine Wisdom', 'This plea for understanding reflects a key theological concept in the Bible: that wisdom and understanding are gifts from God. Many scholars believe that this aligns with James 1:5, which encourages believers to ask God for wisdom. This passage suggests that true understanding of God''s commandments is not solely an intellectual pursuit but requires divine assistance.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God, reinforcing the need for divine insight."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 73, 73, 'kjv', 'that I may learn thy commandments.', 64, 98, 'question', 'Learning Commandments', 'What steps can you take to actively learn and apply God''s commandments in your daily life? Consider how the process of learning involves not just knowledge but also obedience and transformation. How does recognizing that you are ''fashioned'' by God influence your commitment to living according to His ways?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 74, 74, 'kjv', 'They that fear thee will be glad when they see me;', 0, 50, 'connection', 'Fear of the Lord', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 1:7, which states, ''The fear of the Lord is the beginning of knowledge.'' The gladness expressed here reflects the joy found in community among those who revere God. It underscores the mutual encouragement that comes from shared faith and respect for God''s authority, reinforcing the importance of spiritual fellowship.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 1:7", "description": "Highlights the foundational role of fearing the Lord in gaining wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 74, 74, 'kjv', 'because I have hoped in thy word.', 51, 84, 'theology', 'Hope in Scripture', 'This passage suggests that true hope is rooted in God''s word. Many scholars believe that this reflects a broader theological concept that emphasizes the reliability and transformative power of Scripture. The hope mentioned here indicates a profound trust in God''s promises, which aligns with Romans 15:4, where Paul states that Scriptures were written to give us hope. This illustrates the centrality of the Bible in nurturing faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 15:4", "description": "Connects the encouragement and hope derived from Scripture."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 74, 74, 'kjv', 'They that fear thee will be glad when they see me;', 0, 50, 'question', 'Community and Faith', 'How does the joy of others seeing you reflect your own faith journey? In what ways can your hope in God''s word inspire gladness in your community? This prompts reflection on the impact of personal faith on collective joy.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 74, 74, 'kjv', 'because I have hoped in thy word.', 51, 84, 'greek', 'Understanding ''hope''', 'ἔλπις (elpis, G1680) - hope, expectation. This term encapsulates a confident expectation of what is to come, emphasizing the assurance found in God''s promises. The use of ''hope'' here indicates a deep reliance on God''s faithfulness as expressed through His word.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1680", "description": "Highlights the concept of hope in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 75, 75, 'kjv', 'I know, O Lord, that thy judgments are right, and that thou in faithfulness hast afflicted me.', 0, 94, 'connection', 'Judgments and Faithfulness', 'This verse resonates with Romans 8:28, which states that God works all things for good to those who love Him. The acknowledgment of God’s judgments being right emphasizes trust in His sovereignty, even in affliction. It reveals a deep faith that God''s actions, though sometimes painful, are ultimately aligned with His perfect will and goodness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 8:28", "description": "God''s sovereignty and purpose in our lives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 75, 75, 'kjv', 'that thy judgments are right', 16, 44, 'theology', 'Nature of God''s Judgments', 'Many scholars believe that this affirmation of God''s judgments as ''right'' underscores the theological principle of divine justice. It suggests that God''s decisions and actions are inherently good and fair, reflecting His holy character. This reinforces the believer''s confidence in God''s moral order and the ultimate justice that will prevail.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of God''s judgments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 75, 75, 'kjv', 'in faithfulness hast afflicted me.', 60, 94, 'question', 'Understanding Affliction', 'What does it mean to see affliction as an act of God''s faithfulness? How can we reconcile suffering with the belief that God is always faithful? This invites us to reflect on how our trials can lead to spiritual growth and a deeper reliance on God''s promises.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 75, 75, 'kjv', 'I know, O Lord, that thy judgments are right', 0, 44, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Judgments''', 'מִשְׁפָּט (mishpat, H4941) - judgment, justice. This Hebrew term emphasizes the legal and moral dimensions of God''s decisions. It reflects God''s role as the ultimate judge who administers justice in accordance with His perfect will, reinforcing the believer''s trust in His righteous governance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4941", "description": "Strong''s number for the term ''judgment''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 76, 76, 'kjv', 'thy merciful kindness', 18, 39, 'connection', 'God''s Mercy in Psalms', 'The phrase ''thy merciful kindness'' echoes the themes found in Psalms 136:1, which states, ''O give thanks unto the Lord; for he is good: for his mercy endureth forever.'' Both verses highlight God''s enduring mercy, reminding believers of His constant compassion and love. This connection emphasizes the importance of relying on God''s mercy during times of affliction.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 136:1", "description": "Highlights God''s enduring mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 76, 76, 'kjv', 'be for my comfort', 40, 57, 'theology', 'The Role of Comfort', 'This request for comfort indicates a deep understanding of God''s role as a source of solace in times of distress. Many scholars believe this reflects the theological concept of God''s providence, where He provides comfort and support to His followers through His word and presence, reinforcing the need for believers to seek Him in their struggles.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s comfort in affliction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 76, 76, 'kjv', 'according to thy word', 59, 80, 'greek', 'The Word of God', 'דָּבָר (dabar, H1697) - word, matter, thing. This Hebrew term emphasizes the importance of God''s spoken word and promise. It signifies that comfort is not arbitrary but grounded in God''s faithful communication to His people, highlighting the reliability of Scripture as a source of hope and encouragement.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1697", "description": "Refers to the Hebrew word for ''word''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 76, 76, 'kjv', 'thy servant', 86, 97, 'question', 'Understanding Servanthood', 'What does it mean to be a servant of God in the context of seeking comfort? How does acknowledging our status as His servants shape our expectations of His mercy and kindness? Reflecting on this may deepen our understanding of the relationship between servanthood and divine care.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 77, 77, 'kjv', 'Let thy tender mercies come unto me,', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Divine Mercy in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 51:1, where David pleads for God''s mercy: ''Have mercy upon me, O God, according to thy lovingkindness.'' Both verses highlight the believer''s dependence on God''s compassion, emphasizing a theme of seeking divine grace in times of distress. The connection underscores the continuity of God''s mercy throughout the Psalms.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 51:1", "description": "David''s plea for mercy aligns with the request for tender mercies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 77, 77, 'kjv', 'that I may live:', 37, 53, 'theology', 'Life through Mercy', 'This plea suggests that true life, both spiritually and physically, is a gift from God that comes through His mercy. Many scholars believe that this reflects a broader theological theme in Scripture, where life is contingent upon God''s grace and adherence to His commandments, illustrating the intimate connection between divine mercy and human vitality.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 77, 77, 'kjv', 'for thy law is my delight.', 54, 80, 'greek', 'Delight in the Law', 'תּוֹרָה (torah, H8451) - law, instruction, teaching. This term encompasses not just legal stipulations but also God''s guidance for a fulfilling life. The psalmist''s delight in God''s law reflects a deep-seated joy that comes from living in accordance with divine will, contrasting the sorrow found in rebellion against it.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8451", "description": "Strong''s definition of ''torah'' as law and teaching."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 77, 77, 'kjv', 'Let thy tender mercies come unto me, that I may live:', 0, 53, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Mercy', 'In what ways do you actively seek God''s tender mercies in your life? How does recognizing the connection between His mercy and the law shape your understanding of true life in Him?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 78, 78, 'kjv', 'Let the proud be ashamed;', 0, 25, 'connection', 'Pride and Shame', 'This phrase connects well with Proverbs 11:2, which states, ''When pride comes, then comes shame; but with the humble is wisdom.'' Both verses highlight the consequences of pride, emphasizing that those who exalt themselves will ultimately face embarrassment. This connection reinforces the biblical theme that humility is a virtue leading to divine favor.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:2", "description": "Proverbs illustrates the contrast between pride and humility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 78, 78, 'kjv', 'dealt perversely with me without a cause:', 35, 76, 'theology', 'Suffering Innocently', 'This passage suggests a profound theological reflection on the nature of unjust suffering. Many scholars believe this reflects the innocent suffering of the faithful, seen elsewhere in Scripture, such as in Job''s plight. It raises questions about divine justice and the role of God in human suffering, emphasizing trust in God''s law despite adversities.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');